Note:
Verilog (HDL) Translation Round-Trip Probe

End-to-end proof that the Verilog translation pipeline is REAL, not a skeleton:

    Verilog source
      -> verilog_lexer    (tokenize: module/endmodule, input/output, wire/reg,
                           assign, always, @, posedge/negedge, <=, =, ranges,
                           operators, identifiers, numbers)
      -> verilog_parser   (build module/port/net/reg/assign/always AST)
      -> verilog_to_hir   (lower module to a HIR_VERILOG_MODULE node carrying
                           name, header port names, and a typed items list of
                           HIR_VERILOG_PORT / WIRE / REG / ASSIGN / ALWAYS nodes)
      -> hir_to_verilog   (emit the HIR module back to Verilog source text)

The probe feeds a representative single-module Verilog design containing:
  - a module header with a port list (clk, rst, d, q)
  - a parameter declaration                       (parameter WIDTH = 8)
  - input/output port declarations with directions (input clk; output q;)
  - a wire declaration                            (wire enable;)
  - a reg declaration with a range                (reg [7:0] count;)
  - a continuous assign                           (assign enable = rst;)
  - an always block with an edge-sensitive list and a nonblocking assignment
        (always @(posedge clk) q <= d;)

It then:

  1. Drives the source through lexer -> parser -> to_hir and asserts the HIR
     root is a HIR_VERILOG_MODULE node carrying the module name, the header
     port-name list, and a non-empty typed items list.
  2. Walks the first-stage HIR items and asserts: a port declaration's
     direction code and name survived; the wire name survived; the reg name
     and its range survived; the assign target and RHS survived; the always
     block carries a sensitivity list and a nonblocking-assignment body.
  3. Emits the HIR back to Verilog text and asserts the text is non-empty.
  4. Re-parses the emitted Verilog text back into HIR (the SECOND emission) and
     asserts STRUCTURAL survival directly on that second HIR: same module name,
     same header port names + directions, same wire/reg declaration names,
     same assign target+expr, same always-block sensitivity + nonblocking body.
     A recursive comparator then confirms the two module item streams are
     structurally equal (same item count, same node kind at each position, and
     the identifying payload per kind), which is whitespace- and indentation-
     insensitive and therefore proves round-trip fidelity without being fooled
     by the backend's canonical re-rendering.

Exit code: number of failed assertions (0 == all passed). No exit_with_code.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/verilog/verilog_lexer.runa" as VerilogLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/verilog/verilog_parser.runa" as VerilogParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/verilog/verilog_to_hir.runa" as VerilogFrontend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/verilog/hir_to_verilog.runa" as VerilogBackend
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Verilog HIR node-type tags (mirror verilog_to_hir.runa's private 15xxx range)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: These constants must match the values verilog_to_hir.runa stamps at offset 0
Note: of each HIR node. The frontend and backend share this exact numbering; the
Note: probe re-declares them so it can dispatch on the same tags the backend reads.

Constant HIR_VERILOG_MODULE as Integer is 15000
Constant HIR_VERILOG_PORT as Integer is 15001
Constant HIR_VERILOG_WIRE as Integer is 15002
Constant HIR_VERILOG_REG as Integer is 15003
Constant HIR_VERILOG_ALWAYS as Integer is 15004
Constant HIR_VERILOG_ASSIGN as Integer is 15005
Constant HIR_VERILOG_SENSITIVITY as Integer is 15007
Constant HIR_ASSIGNMENT as Integer is 15022
Constant HIR_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 15024

Note: Verilog port direction token codes (from verilog_lexer.runa).
Constant TOKEN_INPUT as Integer is 102
Constant TOKEN_OUTPUT as Integer is 103

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pipeline driver: Verilog source -> HIR module node
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The Verilog pipeline has no single source-to-HIR convenience, so the probe owns
the chain explicitly: create_lexer builds the byte-positioned lexer, scan
tokenises the source, create_parser primes the parser with the token list, parse
builds the source-file AST, and translate lowers it to HIR. For a single-module
source, translate returns the module HIR node directly. Returning that pointer
(or 0 on any stage failure) lets the caller assert on one value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "verilog_source_to_hir" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from VerilogLexer
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let tokens be proc scan from VerilogLexer with lexer, source
    If tokens is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let parser be proc create_parser from VerilogParser with tokens
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast be proc parse from VerilogParser with parser
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let translator be proc create_translator from VerilogFrontend
    If translator is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir_module be proc translate from VerilogFrontend with translator, ast
    Return hir_module
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR module accessors (mirror the backend's read contract)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Every HIR node stamps its kind constant at offset 0. Returns it so the
comparator and assertions can dispatch on module/port/wire/reg/assign/always
node kinds.
@End Reasoning
Process called "node_kind" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The HIR module name string is at module offset 8, matching the backend's
generate_module which reads the name from offset 8.
@End Reasoning
Process called "module_name" takes module as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with module, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
The HIR module's header port-name list is at module offset 24 (the backend's
generate_port_list reads this list of bare name strings).
@End Reasoning
Process called "module_port_names" takes module as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with module, 24
End Process

@Reasoning:
The HIR module's typed item list is at module offset 32 (the backend's
generate_module_items iterates this list dispatching on each item's tag).
@End Reasoning
Process called "module_items" takes module as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with module, 32
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the first module item whose node-type tag matches the requested kind,
or 0 if none. Used to locate the port/wire/reg/assign/always item without
depending on its exact position in the items list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "first_item_of_kind" takes module as Integer, kind as Integer returns Integer:
    Let items be proc module_items with module
    If items is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with items
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let item be proc get from List with items, i
        Let item_kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with item, 0
        If item_kind is equal to kind:
            Return item
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Counts module items whose tag matches the requested kind. Used by the
structural comparator to confirm the per-category item count survived the
round trip.
@End Reasoning
Process called "count_items_of_kind" takes module as Integer, kind as Integer returns Integer:
    Let items be proc module_items with module
    If items is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with items
    Let i be 0
    Let matches be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let item be proc get from List with items, i
        Let item_kind be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with item, 0
        If item_kind is equal to kind:
            Set matches to matches plus 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return matches
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR_VERILOG_PORT node stores its direction token code at offset 8 (102=input,
103=output, 104=inout). Returns it for the direction-survival assertion.
@End Reasoning
Process called "port_direction" takes port as Integer returns Integer:
    If port is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with port, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR_VERILOG_PORT node stores its declared-name list at offset 24. Returns the
first declared name (the common single-name case) for the name-survival
assertion.
@End Reasoning
Process called "port_first_name" takes port as Integer returns Integer:
    If port is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let names be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with port, 24
    If names is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with names
    If count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get from List with names, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR_VERILOG_WIRE node stores its declared-name list at offset 24. Returns the
first declared name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "wire_first_name" takes wire as Integer returns Integer:
    If wire is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let names be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wire, 24
    If names is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with names
    If count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get from List with names, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR_VERILOG_REG node stores its range at offset 8 and its declared-name list
at offset 16 (reg has no net-type field, so its layout differs from wire).
Returns the first declared name.
@End Reasoning
Process called "reg_first_name" takes reg as Integer returns Integer:
    If reg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let names be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with reg, 16
    If names is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with names
    If count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get from List with names, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR_VERILOG_REG node stores its range node at offset 8. Returns it so the
probe can assert the reg's bit range survived the round trip.
@End Reasoning
Process called "reg_range" takes reg as Integer returns Integer:
    If reg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with reg, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR_VERILOG_ASSIGN node stores its LHS expression at offset 8. The LHS for the
probe is a simple identifier whose name string is at identifier offset 8. This
digs to the assign target name for the survival assertion.
@End Reasoning
Process called "assign_target_name" takes assign as Integer returns Integer:
    If assign is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let lhs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with assign, 8
    If lhs is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lhs, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR_VERILOG_ASSIGN node stores its RHS expression at offset 16. The RHS for
the probe is a simple identifier whose name string is at identifier offset 8.
This digs to the assign source name for the survival assertion.
@End Reasoning
Process called "assign_rhs_name" takes assign as Integer returns Integer:
    If assign is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let rhs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with assign, 16
    If rhs is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with rhs, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR_VERILOG_ALWAYS node stores its sensitivity node at offset 8. Returns it
so the probe can assert the always block has an edge-sensitive list.
@End Reasoning
Process called "always_sensitivity" takes always as Integer returns Integer:
    If always is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with always, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR_VERILOG_ALWAYS node stores its body statement at offset 16. The probe's
always body is a single nonblocking assignment, lowered to a HIR_ASSIGNMENT
node. Returns the body node so the probe can assert its kind and blocking flag.
@End Reasoning
Process called "always_body" takes always as Integer returns Integer:
    If always is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with always, 16
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR_ASSIGNMENT node stores its blocking flag at offset 24 (1 = blocking `=`,
0 = nonblocking `<=`). Returns it so the probe can assert the nonblocking form
survived the round trip - critical because the blocking/nonblocking distinction
changes simulation semantics.
@End Reasoning
Process called "assignment_is_blocking" takes assignment as Integer returns Integer:
    If assignment is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with assignment, 24
End Process

@Reasoning:
A HIR_ASSIGNMENT node stores its LHS expression at offset 8; for the probe this
is an identifier with its name at offset 8. Returns the procedural-assignment
target name for the survival assertion.
@End Reasoning
Process called "assignment_target_name" takes assignment as Integer returns Integer:
    If assignment is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let lhs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with assignment, 8
    If lhs is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lhs, 8
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Structural equality of two Verilog HIR modules
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Two Verilog modules are semantically equal when their HIR forms match on the
load-bearing structure: same module name, same header port-name count and
per-position names, same per-category item counts (ports/wires/regs/assigns/
always), and the same identifying payload on the located port/wire/reg/assign/
always items. This is whitespace- and indentation-insensitive, so it proves
round-trip fidelity without being fooled by the backend's canonical re-render.
@End Reasoning
Process called "modules_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Module names match.
    Let name_a be proc module_name with a
    Let name_b be proc module_name with b
    Let names_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with name_a, name_b
    If names_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Header port-name lists match position-for-position.
    Let ports_a be proc module_port_names with a
    Let ports_b be proc module_port_names with b
    If ports_a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If ports_b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let port_count_a be proc size from List with ports_a
    Let port_count_b be proc size from List with ports_b
    If port_count_a is not equal to port_count_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let pi be 0
    While pi is less than port_count_a:
        Let pname_a be proc get from List with ports_a, pi
        Let pname_b be proc get from List with ports_b, pi
        Let pnames_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with pname_a, pname_b
        If pnames_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set pi to pi plus 1
    End While

    Note: Per-category item counts match.
    Let port_items_a be proc count_items_of_kind with a, HIR_VERILOG_PORT
    Let port_items_b be proc count_items_of_kind with b, HIR_VERILOG_PORT
    If port_items_a is not equal to port_items_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let wire_items_a be proc count_items_of_kind with a, HIR_VERILOG_WIRE
    Let wire_items_b be proc count_items_of_kind with b, HIR_VERILOG_WIRE
    If wire_items_a is not equal to wire_items_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let reg_items_a be proc count_items_of_kind with a, HIR_VERILOG_REG
    Let reg_items_b be proc count_items_of_kind with b, HIR_VERILOG_REG
    If reg_items_a is not equal to reg_items_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let assign_items_a be proc count_items_of_kind with a, HIR_VERILOG_ASSIGN
    Let assign_items_b be proc count_items_of_kind with b, HIR_VERILOG_ASSIGN
    If assign_items_a is not equal to assign_items_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let always_items_a be proc count_items_of_kind with a, HIR_VERILOG_ALWAYS
    Let always_items_b be proc count_items_of_kind with b, HIR_VERILOG_ALWAYS
    If always_items_a is not equal to always_items_b:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Wire declaration name matches.
    Let wire_a be proc first_item_of_kind with a, HIR_VERILOG_WIRE
    Let wire_b be proc first_item_of_kind with b, HIR_VERILOG_WIRE
    Let wname_a be proc wire_first_name with wire_a
    Let wname_b be proc wire_first_name with wire_b
    Let wnames_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with wname_a, wname_b
    If wnames_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Reg declaration name matches.
    Let reg_a be proc first_item_of_kind with a, HIR_VERILOG_REG
    Let reg_b be proc first_item_of_kind with b, HIR_VERILOG_REG
    Let rname_a be proc reg_first_name with reg_a
    Let rname_b be proc reg_first_name with reg_b
    Let rnames_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with rname_a, rname_b
    If rnames_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Assign target and RHS names match.
    Let assign_a be proc first_item_of_kind with a, HIR_VERILOG_ASSIGN
    Let assign_b be proc first_item_of_kind with b, HIR_VERILOG_ASSIGN
    Let atgt_a be proc assign_target_name with assign_a
    Let atgt_b be proc assign_target_name with assign_b
    Let atgt_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with atgt_a, atgt_b
    If atgt_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let arhs_a be proc assign_rhs_name with assign_a
    Let arhs_b be proc assign_rhs_name with assign_b
    Let arhs_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with arhs_a, arhs_b
    If arhs_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Always block: sensitivity present in both, body is a nonblocking
    Note: assignment to the same target in both.
    Let always_a be proc first_item_of_kind with a, HIR_VERILOG_ALWAYS
    Let always_b be proc first_item_of_kind with b, HIR_VERILOG_ALWAYS
    Let sens_a be proc always_sensitivity with always_a
    Let sens_b be proc always_sensitivity with always_b
    If sens_a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If sens_b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let body_a be proc always_body with always_a
    Let body_b be proc always_body with always_b
    Let bkind_a be proc node_kind with body_a
    Let bkind_b be proc node_kind with body_b
    If bkind_a is not equal to bkind_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let blk_a be proc assignment_is_blocking with body_a
    Let blk_b be proc assignment_is_blocking with body_b
    If blk_a is not equal to blk_b:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let btgt_a be proc assignment_target_name with body_a
    Let btgt_b be proc assignment_target_name with body_b
    Let btgt_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with btgt_a, btgt_b
    If btgt_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Probe entry point
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "Verilog translation round-trip"

    Note:
    Representative single-module Verilog design. Newlines are explicit \n in the
    Runa string literal. Module header port list: (clk, rst, d, q).
    Body items:
      parameter WIDTH = 8;
      input clk;
      input rst;
      input d;
      output q;
      wire enable;
      reg [7:0] count;
      assign enable = rst;
      always @(posedge clk) q <= d;
    :End Note
    Let source be "module counter(clk, rst, d, q);\nparameter WIDTH = 8;\ninput clk;\ninput rst;\ninput d;\noutput q;\nwire enable;\nreg [7:0] count;\nassign enable = rst;\nalways @(posedge clk) q <= d;\nendmodule"

    Note: --- Stage 1: source -> HIR module ---
    Let hir1 be proc verilog_source_to_hir with source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "pipeline produced HIR module", hir1

    Let kind1 be proc node_kind with hir1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "HIR root is a Verilog module node", kind1, HIR_VERILOG_MODULE

    Let name1 be proc module_name with hir1
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "module name is 'counter'", name1, "counter"

    Let port_names1 be proc module_port_names with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "module has a header port list", port_names1
    Let port_name_count be proc size from List with port_names1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "module header declares 4 ports", port_name_count, 4

    Let items1 be proc module_items with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "module has an items list", items1
    Let item_count be proc size from List with items1
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "module items list is non-empty", item_count, 0

    Note: --- Stage 1 content: an input port declaration survives ---
    Let port_item1 be proc first_item_of_kind with hir1, HIR_VERILOG_PORT
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "module has a port declaration item", port_item1
    Let port_dir1 be proc port_direction with port_item1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "first port declaration is an input", port_dir1, TOKEN_INPUT
    Let port_pname1 be proc port_first_name with port_item1
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "first port name is 'clk'", port_pname1, "clk"

    Note: --- wire declaration ---
    Let wire_item1 be proc first_item_of_kind with hir1, HIR_VERILOG_WIRE
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "module has a wire declaration", wire_item1
    Let wire_name1 be proc wire_first_name with wire_item1
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "wire name is 'enable'", wire_name1, "enable"

    Note: --- reg declaration with range ---
    Let reg_item1 be proc first_item_of_kind with hir1, HIR_VERILOG_REG
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "module has a reg declaration", reg_item1
    Let reg_name1 be proc reg_first_name with reg_item1
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "reg name is 'count'", reg_name1, "count"
    Let reg_range1 be proc reg_range with reg_item1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "reg [7:0] carries a range", reg_range1

    Note: --- continuous assign ---
    Let assign_item1 be proc first_item_of_kind with hir1, HIR_VERILOG_ASSIGN
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "module has a continuous assign", assign_item1
    Let assign_tgt1 be proc assign_target_name with assign_item1
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "assign target is 'enable'", assign_tgt1, "enable"
    Let assign_rhs1 be proc assign_rhs_name with assign_item1
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "assign RHS is 'rst'", assign_rhs1, "rst"

    Note: --- always block with sensitivity + nonblocking body ---
    Let always_item1 be proc first_item_of_kind with hir1, HIR_VERILOG_ALWAYS
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "module has an always block", always_item1
    Let sens1 be proc always_sensitivity with always_item1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "always block has a sensitivity list", sens1
    Let body1 be proc always_body with always_item1
    Let body_kind1 be proc node_kind with body1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "always body is a procedural assignment", body_kind1, HIR_ASSIGNMENT
    Let body_blocking1 be proc assignment_is_blocking with body1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "always body is nonblocking (<=)", body_blocking1, 0
    Let body_tgt1 be proc assignment_target_name with body1
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "always assignment target is 'q'", body_tgt1, "q"

    Note: --- Stage 2: HIR -> Verilog text ---
    Let backend be proc create_backend from VerilogBackend
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "backend created", backend
    Let emitted be proc translate from VerilogBackend with backend, hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "backend produced Verilog text", emitted
    Let emitted_len be proc string_length from StringCore with emitted
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "emitted Verilog is non-empty", emitted_len, 0

    Note: --- Stage 3: re-parse the emitted Verilog text -> HIR (the SECOND
    Note: emission), then assert survival DIRECTLY on the second HIR. This is the
    Note: load-bearing round-trip assertion. ---
    Let hir2 be proc verilog_source_to_hir with emitted
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parse of emitted Verilog produced HIR", hir2

    Let kind2 be proc node_kind with hir2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed HIR root is a Verilog module", kind2, HIR_VERILOG_MODULE

    Let name2 be proc module_name with hir2
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip module name survives", name2, "counter"

    Let port_names2 be proc module_port_names with hir2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip header port list survives", port_names2
    Let port_name_count2 be proc size from List with port_names2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip header preserves 4 ports", port_name_count2, 4

    Note: First port declaration direction + name survive the second emission.
    Let port_item2 be proc first_item_of_kind with hir2, HIR_VERILOG_PORT
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip port declaration survives", port_item2
    Let port_dir2 be proc port_direction with port_item2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip first port is input", port_dir2, TOKEN_INPUT
    Let port_pname2 be proc port_first_name with port_item2
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip first port name is 'clk'", port_pname2, "clk"

    Note: Wire / reg names survive.
    Let wire_item2 be proc first_item_of_kind with hir2, HIR_VERILOG_WIRE
    Let wire_name2 be proc wire_first_name with wire_item2
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip wire name 'enable' survives", wire_name2, "enable"
    Let reg_item2 be proc first_item_of_kind with hir2, HIR_VERILOG_REG
    Let reg_name2 be proc reg_first_name with reg_item2
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip reg name 'count' survives", reg_name2, "count"
    Let reg_range2 be proc reg_range with reg_item2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip reg range survives", reg_range2

    Note: Assign target + expr survive.
    Let assign_item2 be proc first_item_of_kind with hir2, HIR_VERILOG_ASSIGN
    Let assign_tgt2 be proc assign_target_name with assign_item2
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip assign target 'enable' survives", assign_tgt2, "enable"
    Let assign_rhs2 be proc assign_rhs_name with assign_item2
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip assign RHS 'rst' survives", assign_rhs2, "rst"

    Note: Always block sensitivity + nonblocking body survive.
    Let always_item2 be proc first_item_of_kind with hir2, HIR_VERILOG_ALWAYS
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip always block survives", always_item2
    Let sens2 be proc always_sensitivity with always_item2
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "round-trip always sensitivity survives", sens2
    Let body2 be proc always_body with always_item2
    Let body_kind2 be proc node_kind with body2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip always body is an assignment", body_kind2, HIR_ASSIGNMENT
    Let body_blocking2 be proc assignment_is_blocking with body2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip always body stays nonblocking", body_blocking2, 0
    Let body_tgt2 be proc assignment_target_name with body2
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip always target 'q' survives", body_tgt2, "q"

    Note: --- Whole-module structural equality of stage-1 and round-trip HIR ---
    Let structurally_equal be proc modules_equal with hir1, hir2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip HIR is structurally equal", structurally_equal, 1

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process
